# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gene-expression-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] A **DNA microarray** (also commonly known as a **DNA chip** or **biochip**) is a collection of microscopic DNA spots attached to a solid surface.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Scientists use DNA microarrays to measure the expression levels of large numbers of genes simultaneously or to genotype multiple regions of a genome.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Each DNA spot contains picomoles (10−12 moles) of a specific DNA sequence, known as *probes* (or *reporters* or *oligos*).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] These can be a short section of a gene or other DNA element that are used to hybridize a cDNA or cRNA (also called anti-sense RNA) sample (called *target*) under high-stringency conditions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Probe-target hybridization is usually detected and quantified by detection of fluorophore-, silver-, or chemiluminescence-labeled targets to determine relative abundance of nucleic acid sequences in the target.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The original nucleic acid arrays were macro arrays approximately 9 cm × 12 cm and the first computerized image based analysis was published in 1981.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] An example of its application is in SNPs arrays for polymorphisms in cardiovascular diseases, cancer, pathogens and GWAS analysis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] It is also used for the identification of structural variations and the measurement of gene expression.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The core principle behind microarrays is hybridization between two DNA strands, the property of complementary nucleic acid sequences to specifically pair with each other by forming hydrogen bonds between complementary nucleotide base pairs.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] A high number of complementary base pairs in a nucleotide sequence means tighter non-covalent bonding between the two strands.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] After washing off non-specific bonding sequences, only strongly paired strands will remain hybridized.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Fluorescently labeled target sequences that bind to a probe sequence generate a signal that depends on the hybridization conditions (such as temperature), and washing after hybridization.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Total strength of the signal, from a spot (feature), depends upon the amount of target sample binding to the probes present on that spot.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Microarrays use relative quantitation in which the intensity of a feature is compared to the intensity of the same feature under a different condition, and the identity of the feature is known by its position.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] DNA microarrays can be used to detect DNA (as in comparative genomic hybridization), or detect RNA (most commonly as cDNA after reverse transcription) that may or may not be translated into proteins.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The process of measuring gene expression via cDNA is called expression analysis or expression profiling.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Specialised arrays tailored to particular crops are becoming increasingly popular in molecular breeding applications.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] In the future they could be used to screen seedlings at early stages to lower the number of unneeded seedlings tried out in breeding operations.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Microarrays can be manufactured in different ways, depending on the number of probes under examination, costs, customization requirements, and the type of scientific question being asked.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Arrays from commercial vendors may have as few as 10 probes or as many as 5 million or more micrometre-scale probes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Microarrays can be fabricated using a variety of technologies, including printing with fine-pointed pins onto glass slides, photolithography using pre-made masks, photolithography using dynamic micromirror devices, ink-jet printing, or electrochemistry on microelectrode arrays.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] In *spotted microarrays*, the probes are oligonucleotides, cDNA or small fragments of PCR products that correspond to mRNAs.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The probes are synthesized prior to deposition on the array surface and are then "spotted" onto glass.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] A common approach utilizes an array of fine pins or needles controlled by a robotic arm that is dipped into wells containing DNA probes and then depositing each probe at designated locations on the array surface.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The resulting "grid" of probes represents the nucleic acid profiles of the prepared probes and is ready to receive complementary cDNA or cRNA "targets" derived from experimental or clinical samples.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] This technique is used by research scientists around the world to produce "in-house" printed microarrays in their own labs.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] These arrays may be easily customized for each experiment, because researchers can choose the probes and printing locations on the arrays, synthesize the probes in their own lab (or collaborating facility), and spot the arrays.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] They can then generate their own labeled samples for hybridization, hybridize the samples to the array, and finally scan the arrays with their own equipment.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] This provides a relatively low-cost microarray that may be customized for each study, and avoids the costs of purchasing often more expensive commercial arrays that may represent vast numbers of genes that are not of interest to the investigator.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Publications exist which indicate in-house spotted microarrays may not provide the same level of sensitivity compared to commercial oligonucleotide arrays, possibly owing to the small batch sizes and reduced printing efficiencies when compared to industrial manufactures of oligo arrays.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] In *oligonucleotide microarrays*, the probes are short sequences designed to match parts of the sequence of known or predicted open reading frames.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Although oligonucleotide probes are often used in "spotted" microarrays, the term "oligonucleotide array" most often refers to a specific technique of manufacturing.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Oligonucleotide arrays are produced by printing short oligonucleotide sequences designed to represent a single gene or family of gene splice-variants by synthesizing this sequence directly onto the array surface instead of depositing intact sequences.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] One technique used to produce oligonucleotide arrays include photolithographic synthesis (Affymetrix) on a silica substrate where light and light-sensitive masking agents are used to "build" a sequence one nucleotide at a time across the entire array.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Each applicable probe is selectively "unmasked" prior to bathing the array in a solution of a single nucleotide, then a masking reaction takes place and the next set of probes are unmasked in preparation for a different nucleotide exposure.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] After many repetitions, the sequences of every probe become fully constructed.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] More recently, Maskless Array Synthesis from NimbleGen Systems has combined flexibility with large numbers of probes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Oligonucleotide microarrays often carry control probes designed to hybridize with RNA spike-ins.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The degree of hybridization between the spike-ins and the control probes is used to normalize the hybridization measurements for the target probes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Although absolute levels of gene expression may be determined in the two-color array in rare instances, the relative differences in expression among different spots within a sample and between samples is the preferred method of data analysis for the two-color system.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Examples of providers for such microarrays includes Agilent with their Dual-Mode platform, Eppendorf with their DualChip platform for colorimetric Silverquant labeling, and TeleChem International with Arrayit.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] In *single-channel microarrays* or *one-color microarrays*, the arrays provide intensity data for each probe or probe set indicating a relative level of hybridization with the labeled target.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] However, they do not truly indicate abundance levels of a gene but rather relative abundance when compared to other samples or conditions when processed in the same experiment.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Each RNA molecule encounters protocol and batch-specific bias during amplification, labeling, and hybridization phases of the experiment making comparisons between genes for the same microarray uninformative.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The comparison of two conditions for the same gene requires two separate single-dye hybridizations.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Several popular single-channel systems are the Affymetrix "Gene Chip", Illumina "Bead Chip", Agilent single-channel arrays, the Applied Microarrays "CodeLink" arrays, and the Eppendorf "DualChip & Silverquant".
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Another benefit is that data are more easily compared to arrays from different experiments as long as batch effects have been accounted for.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] One channel microarray may be the only choice in some situations.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Suppose i samples need to be compared: then the number of experiments required using the two channel arrays quickly becomes unfeasible, unless a sample is used as a reference.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] This is an example of a **DNA microarray experiment** which includes details for a particular case to better explain DNA microarray experiments, while listing modifications for RNA or other alternative experiments.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The nucleic acid of interest is purified: this can be RNA for expression profiling, DNA for comparative hybridization, or DNA/RNA bound to a particular protein which is immunoprecipitated (ChIP-on-chip) for epigenetic or regulation studies.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] In this example total RNA is isolated (both nuclear and cytoplasmic) by guanidinium thiocyanate-phenol-chloroform extraction (e.g.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Trizol) which isolates most RNA (whereas column methods have a cut off of 200 nucleotides) and if done correctly has a better purity.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The purified RNA is analysed for quality (by capillary electrophoresis) and quantity (for example, by using a NanoDrop or NanoPhotometer spectrometer).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] If the material is of acceptable quality and sufficient quantity is present (e.g., >1μg, although the required amount varies by microarray platform), the experiment can proceed.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The labeled product is generated via reverse transcription and followed by an optional PCR amplification.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The RNA is reverse transcribed with either polyT primers (which amplify only mRNA) or random primers (which amplify all RNA, most of which is rRNA). miRNA microarrays ligate an oligonucleotide to the purified small RNA (isolated with a fractionator), which is then reverse transcribed and amplified.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The labeled samples are then mixed with a proprietary hybridization solution which can consist of SDS, SSC, dextran sulfate, a blocking agent (such as Cot-1 DNA, salmon sperm DNA, calf thymus DNA, PolyA, or PolyT), Denhardt's solution, or formamine.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The mixture is denatured and added to the pinholes of the microarray.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The holes are sealed and the microarray hybridized, either in a hyb oven, where the microarray is mixed by rotation, or in a mixer, where the microarray is mixed by alternating pressure at the pinholes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] After an overnight hybridization, all nonspecific binding is washed off (SDS and SSC).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The microarray is dried and scanned by a machine that uses a laser to excite the dye and measures the emission levels with a detector.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The image is gridded with a template and the intensities of each feature (composed of several pixels) is quantified.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The raw data is normalized; the simplest normalization method is to subtract background intensity and scale so that the total intensities of the features of the two channels are equal, or to use the intensity of a reference gene to calculate the t-value for all of the intensities.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] More sophisticated methods include z-ratio, loess and lowess regression and RMA (robust multichip analysis) for Affymetrix chips (single-channel, silicon chip, *in situ* synthesized short oligonucleotides).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Due to the biological complexity of gene expression, the considerations of experimental design that are discussed in the expression profiling article are of critical importance if statistically and biologically valid conclusions are to be drawn from the data.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] There are three main elements to consider when designing a microarray experiment.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] First, replication of the biological samples is essential for drawing conclusions from the experiment.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Second, technical replicates (e.g. two RNA samples obtained from each experimental unit) may help to quantitate precision.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The biological replicates include independent RNA extractions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Technical replicates may be two aliquots of the same extraction.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Third, spots of each cDNA clone or oligonucleotide are present as replicates (at least duplicates) on the microarray slide, to provide a measure of technical precision in each hybridization.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] It is critical that information about the sample preparation and handling is discussed, in order to help identify the independent units in the experiment and to avoid inflated estimates of statistical significance.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Microarray data is difficult to exchange due to the lack of standardization in platform fabrication, assay protocols, and analysis methods.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] This presents an interoperability problem in bioinformatics.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] For example, the "Minimum Information About a Microarray Experiment" (MIAME) checklist helps define the level of detail that should exist and is being adopted by many journals as a requirement for the submission of papers incorporating microarray results.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] But MIAME does not describe the format for the information, so while many formats can support the MIAME requirements, as of 2007 no format permits verification of complete semantic compliance.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The "MicroArray Quality Control (MAQC) Project" is being conducted by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) to develop standards and quality control metrics which will eventually allow the use of MicroArray data in drug discovery, clinical practice and regulatory decision-making.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The MGED Society has developed standards for the representation of gene expression experiment results and relevant annotations.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Microarray data sets are commonly very large, and analytical precision is influenced by a number of variables.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Statistical challenges include taking into account effects of background noise and appropriate normalization of the data.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Normalization methods may be suited to specific platforms and, in the case of commercial platforms, the analysis may be proprietary.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Microarray data may require further processing aimed at reducing the dimensionality of the data to aid comprehension and more focused analysis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Other methods permit analysis of data consisting of a low number of biological or technical replicates; for example, the Local Pooled Error (LPE) test pools standard deviations of genes with similar expression levels in an effort to compensate for insufficient replication.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The relation between a probe and the mRNA that it is expected to detect is not trivial.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Some mRNAs may cross-hybridize probes in the array that are supposed to detect another mRNA.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] In addition, mRNAs may experience amplification bias that is sequence or molecule-specific.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Thirdly, probes that are designed to detect the mRNA of a particular gene may be relying on genomic EST information that is incorrectly associated with that gene.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Microarray data was found to be more useful when compared to other similar datasets.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] The sheer volume of data, specialized formats (such as MIAME), and curation efforts associated with the datasets require specialized databases to store the data.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] A number of open-source data warehousing solutions, such as InterMine and BioMart, have been created for the specific purpose of integrating diverse biological datasets, and also support analysis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Advances in massively parallel sequencing has led to the development of RNA-Seq technology, that enables a whole transcriptome shotgun approach to characterize and quantify gene expression.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/dna-microarray] Unlike microarrays, which need a reference genome and transcriptome to be available before the microarray itself can be designed, RNA-Seq can also be used for new model organisms whose genome has not been sequenced yet.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/fold-change] Fold change is so called because it is common to describe an increase of multiple *X* as an "*X*-fold increase".
[src:gene-expression-analysis/fold-change] As such, several dictionaries, including the Oxford English Dictionary and Merriam-Webster Dictionary, as well as Collins's Dictionary of Mathematics, define "-fold" to mean "times", as in "2-fold" = "2 times" = "double".
[src:gene-expression-analysis/fold-change] Likely because of this definition, many scientists use not only "fold", but also "fold change" to be synonymous with "times", as in "3-fold larger" = "3 times larger".
[src:gene-expression-analysis/fold-change] Fold change is often used in analysis of gene expression data from microarray and RNA-Seq experiments for measuring change in the expression level of a gene.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/fold-change] A disadvantage of using fold change occurs when the denominator is close to zero.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/fold-change] In this case, the ratio may be difficult to interpret because the fold change value can be disproportionately affected by measurement noise.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/fold-change] In the field of genomics (and more generally in bioinformatics), the modern usage is to define fold change in terms of ratios, and not by the alternative definition.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/fold-change] However, log-ratios are often used for analysis and visualization of fold changes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/fold-change] The logarithm to base 2 is most commonly used, as it is easy to interpret, e.g. a doubling in the original scaling is equal to a log2 fold change of 1, a quadrupling is equal to a log2 fold change of 2 and so on.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/fold-change] Conversely, the measure is symmetric when the change decreases by an equivalent amount e.g. a halving is equal to a log2 fold change of −1, a quartering is equal to a log2 fold change of −2 and so on.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/fold-change] This leads to more aesthetically pleasing plots, as exponential changes are displayed as linear and so the dynamic range is increased.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/fold-change] For example, on a plot axis showing log2 fold changes, an 8-fold increase will be displayed at an axis value of 3 (since 23 = 8).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/fold-change] However, there is no mathematical reason to only use logarithm to base 2, and due to many discrepancies in describing the log2 fold changes in gene/protein expression, a new term "loget" has been proposed.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] In the field of molecular biology, **gene expression profiling** is the measurement of the activity (the expression) of thousands of genes at once, to create a global picture of cellular function.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] These profiles can, for example, distinguish between cells that are actively dividing, or show how the cells react to a particular treatment.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Many experiments of this sort measure an entire genome simultaneously, that is, every gene present in a particular cell.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Several transcriptomics technologies can be used to generate the necessary data to analyse.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] DNA microarrays measure the relative activity of previously identified target genes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Sequence based techniques, like RNA-Seq, provide information on the sequences of genes in addition to their expression level.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Expression profiling is a logical next step after sequencing a genome: the sequence tells us what the cell could possibly do, while the expression profile tells us what it is actually doing at a point in time.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Genes contain the instructions for making messenger RNA (mRNA), but at any moment each cell makes mRNA from only a fraction of the genes it carries.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] If a gene is used to produce mRNA, it is considered "on", otherwise "off".
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Many factors determine whether a gene is on or off, such as the time of day, whether or not the cell is actively dividing, its local environment, and chemical signals from other cells.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] For instance, skin cells, liver cells and nerve cells turn on (express) somewhat different genes and that is in large part what makes them different.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Therefore, an expression profile allows one to deduce a cell's type, state, environment, and so forth.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Expression profiling experiments often involve measuring the relative amount of mRNA expressed in two or more experimental conditions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] This is because altered levels of a specific sequence of mRNA suggest a changed need for the protein coded by the mRNA, perhaps indicating a homeostatic response or a pathological condition.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] For example, higher levels of mRNA coding for alcohol dehydrogenase suggest that the cells or tissues under study are responding to increased levels of ethanol in their environment.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Similarly, if breast cancer cells express higher levels of mRNA associated with a particular transmembrane receptor than normal cells do, it might be that this receptor plays a role in breast cancer.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] A drug that interferes with this receptor may prevent or treat breast cancer.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] In developing a drug, one may perform gene expression profiling experiments to help assess the drug's toxicity, perhaps by looking for changing levels in the expression of cytochrome P450 genes, which may be a biomarker of drug metabolism.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Gene expression profiling may become an important diagnostic test.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] The human genome contains on the order of 20,000 genes which work in concert to produce roughly 1,000,000 distinct proteins.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] This is due to alternative splicing, and also because cells make important changes to proteins through posttranslational modification after they first construct them, so a given gene serves as the basis for many possible versions of a particular protein.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] In any case, a single mass spectrometry experiment can identify about 2,000 proteins or 0.2% of the total.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] While knowledge of the precise proteins a cell makes (proteomics) is more relevant than knowing how much messenger RNA is made from each gene, gene expression profiling provides the most global picture possible in a single experiment.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] However, proteomics methodology is improving.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] In other species, such as yeast, it is possible to identify over 4,000 proteins in just over one hour.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Sometimes, a scientist already has an idea of what is going on, a hypothesis, and he or she performs an expression profiling experiment with the idea of potentially disproving this hypothesis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] In other words, the scientist is making a specific prediction about levels of expression that could turn out to be false.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] More commonly, expression profiling takes place before enough is known about how genes interact with experimental conditions for a testable hypothesis to exist.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] With no hypothesis, there is nothing to disprove, but expression profiling can help to identify a candidate hypothesis for future experiments.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Most early expression profiling experiments, and many current ones, have this form which is known as class discovery.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] A popular approach to class discovery involves grouping similar genes or samples together using one of the many existing clustering methods such the traditional k-means or hierarchical clustering, or the more recent MCL.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Apart from selecting a clustering algorithm, user usually has to choose an appropriate proximity measure (distance or similarity) between data objects.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] The figure above represents the output of a two dimensional cluster, in which similar samples (rows, above) and similar gene probes (columns) were organized so that they would lie close together.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] The simplest form of class discovery would be to list all the genes that changed by more than a certain amount between two experimental conditions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Class prediction is more difficult than class discovery, but it allows one to answer questions of direct clinical significance such as, given this profile, what is the probability that this patient will respond to this drug?
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] This requires many examples of profiles that responded and did not respond, as well as cross-validation techniques to discriminate between them.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] In general, expression profiling studies report those genes that showed statistically significant differences under changed experimental conditions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] This is typically a small fraction of the genome for several reasons.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] First, different cells and tissues express a subset of genes as a direct consequence of cellular differentiation so many genes are turned off.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Second, many of the genes code for proteins that are required for survival in very specific amounts so many genes do not change.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Third, cells use many other mechanisms to regulate proteins in addition to altering the amount of mRNA, so these genes may stay consistently expressed even when protein concentrations are rising and falling.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Fourth, financial constraints limit expression profiling experiments to a small number of observations of the same gene under identical conditions, reducing the statistical power of the experiment, making it impossible for the experiment to identify important but subtle changes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Finally, it takes a great amount of effort to discuss the biological significance of each regulated gene, so scientists often limit their discussion to a subset.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Newer microarray analysis techniques automate certain aspects of attaching biological significance to expression profiling results, but this remains a very difficult problem.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] The relatively short length of gene lists published from expression profiling experiments limits the extent to which experiments performed in different laboratories appear to agree.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Placing expression profiling results in a publicly accessible microarray database makes it possible for researchers to assess expression patterns beyond the scope of published results, perhaps identifying similarity with their own work.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Both DNA microarrays and quantitative PCR exploit the preferential binding or "base pairing" of complementary nucleic acid sequences, and both are used in gene expression profiling, often in a serial fashion.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] While high throughput DNA microarrays lack the quantitative accuracy of qPCR, it takes about the same time to measure the gene expression of a few dozen genes via qPCR as it would to measure an entire genome using DNA microarrays.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] So it often makes sense to perform semi-quantitative DNA microarray analysis experiments to identify candidate genes, then perform qPCR on some of the most interesting candidate genes to validate the microarray results.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Other experiments, such as a Western blot of some of the protein products of differentially expressed genes, make conclusions based on the expression profile more persuasive, since the mRNA levels do not necessarily correlate to the amount of expressed protein.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Data analysis of microarrays has become an area of intense research.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Simply stating that a group of genes were regulated by at least twofold, once a common practice, lacks a solid statistical footing.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] With five or fewer replicates in each group, typical for microarrays, a single outlier observation can create an apparent difference greater than two-fold.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] In addition, arbitrarily setting the bar at two-fold is not biologically sound, as it eliminates from consideration many genes with obvious biological significance.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Rather than identify differentially expressed genes using a fold change cutoff, one can use a variety of statistical tests or omnibus tests such as ANOVA, all of which consider both fold change and variability to create a p-value, an estimate of how often we would observe the data by chance alone.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Applying p-values to microarrays is complicated by the large number of multiple comparisons (genes) involved.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] For example, a p-value of 0.05 is typically thought to indicate significance, since it estimates a 5% probability of observing the data by chance.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] But with 10,000 genes on a microarray, 500 genes would be identified as significant at p < 0.05 even if there were no difference between the experimental groups.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] One obvious solution is to consider significant only those genes meeting a much more stringent p value criterion, e.g., one could perform a Bonferroni correction on the p-values, or use a false discovery rate calculation to adjust p-values in proportion to the number of parallel tests involved.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Unfortunately, these approaches may reduce the number of significant genes to zero, even when genes are in fact differentially expressed.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Current statistics such as Rank products aim to strike a balance between false discovery of genes due to chance variation and non-discovery of differentially expressed genes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Commonly cited methods include the Significance Analysis of Microarrays (SAM) and a wide variety of methods are available from Bioconductor and a variety of analysis packages from bioinformatics companies.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Selecting a different test usually identifies a different list of significant genes since each test operates under a specific set of assumptions, and places a different emphasis on certain features in the data.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Many tests begin with the assumption of a normal distribution in the data, because that seems like a sensible starting point and often produces results that appear more significant.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Some tests consider the joint distribution of all gene observations to estimate general variability in measurements, while others look at each gene in isolation.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Many modern microarray analysis techniques involve bootstrapping (statistics), machine learning or Monte Carlo methods.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] As the number of replicate measurements in a microarray experiment increases, various statistical approaches yield increasingly similar results, but lack of concordance between different statistical methods makes array results appear less trustworthy.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] The MAQC Project makes recommendations to guide researchers in selecting more standard methods (e.g. using p-value and fold-change together for selecting the differentially expressed genes) so that experiments performed in different laboratories will agree better.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Different from the analysis on differentially expressed individual genes, another type of analysis focuses on differential expression or perturbation of pre-defined gene sets and is called gene set analysis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Gene set analysis demonstrated several major advantages over individual gene differential expression analysis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Gene sets are groups of genes that are functionally related according to current knowledge.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Therefore, gene set analysis is considered a knowledge based analysis approach.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Commonly used gene sets include those derived from KEGG pathways, Gene Ontology terms, gene groups that share some other functional annotations, such as common transcriptional regulators etc.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] While the statistics may identify which gene products change under experimental conditions, making biological sense of expression profiling rests on knowing which protein each gene product makes and what function this protein performs.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Gene annotation provides functional and other information, for example the location of each gene within a particular chromosome.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Some functional annotations are more reliable than others; some are absent.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Gene annotation databases change regularly, and various databases refer to the same protein by different names, reflecting a changing understanding of protein function.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Use of standardized gene nomenclature helps address the naming aspect of the problem, but exact matching of transcripts to genes remains an important consideration.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Having identified some set of regulated genes, the next step in expression profiling involves looking for patterns within the regulated set.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Do the proteins made from these genes perform similar functions?
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Do they reside in similar parts of the cell?
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Gene ontology analysis provides a standard way to define these relationships.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Gene ontologies start with very broad categories, e.g., "metabolic process" and break them down into smaller categories, e.g., "carbohydrate metabolic process" and finally into quite restrictive categories like "inositol and derivative phosphorylation".
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Genes have other attributes beside biological function, chemical properties and cellular location.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] One can compose sets of genes based on proximity to other genes, association with a disease, and relationships with drugs or toxins.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] The Molecular Signatures Database and the Comparative Toxicogenomics Database are examples of resources to categorize genes in numerous ways.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Regulated genes are categorized in terms of what they are and what they do, important relationships between genes may emerge.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] For example, we might see evidence that a certain gene creates a protein to make an enzyme that activates a protein to turn on a second gene on our list.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] This second gene may be a transcription factor that regulates yet another gene from our list.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Observing these links we may begin to suspect that they represent much more than chance associations in the results, and that they are all on our list because of an underlying biological process.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] On the other hand, it could be that if one selected genes at random, one might find many that seem to have something in common.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] In this sense, we need rigorous statistical procedures to test whether the emerging biological themes is significant or not.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] That is where gene set analysis comes in.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Fairly straightforward statistics provide estimates of whether associations between genes on lists are greater than what one would expect by chance.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] These statistics are interesting, even if they represent a substantial oversimplification of what is really going on.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Suppose there are 10,000 genes in an experiment, only 50 (0.5%) of which play a known role in making cholesterol.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] The experiment identifies 200 regulated genes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Of those, 40 (20%) turn out to be on a list of cholesterol genes as well.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Based on the overall prevalence of the cholesterol genes (0.5%) one expects an average of 1 cholesterol gene for every 200 regulated genes, that is, 0.005 times 200.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] This expectation is an average, so one expects to see more than one some of the time.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] The question becomes how often we would see 40 instead of 1 due to pure chance.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] According to the hypergeometric distribution, one would expect to try about 10^57 times (10 followed by 56 zeroes) before picking 39 or more of the cholesterol genes from a pool of 10,000 by drawing 200 genes at random.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Whether one pays much attention to how infinitesimally small the probability of observing this by chance is, one would conclude that the regulated gene list is enriched in genes with a known cholesterol association.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] One might further hypothesize that the experimental treatment regulates cholesterol, because the treatment seems to selectively regulate genes associated with cholesterol.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] While this may be true, there are a number of reasons why making this a firm conclusion based on enrichment alone represents an unwarranted leap of faith.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] It is quite possible that the amount of these cholesterol-related proteins remains constant under the experimental conditions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Second, even if protein levels do change, perhaps there is always enough of them around to make cholesterol as fast as it can be possibly made, that is, another protein, not on our list, is the rate determining step in the process of making cholesterol.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Finally, proteins typically play many roles, so these genes may be regulated not because of their shared association with making cholesterol but because of a shared role in a completely independent process.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Bearing the foregoing caveats in mind, while gene profiles do not in themselves prove causal relationships between treatments and biological effects, they do offer unique biological insights that would often be very difficult to arrive at in other ways.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] As described above, one can identify significantly regulated genes first and then find patterns by comparing the list of significant genes to sets of genes known to share certain associations.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] One can also work the problem in reverse order.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Suppose there are 40 genes associated with a known process, for example, a predisposition to diabetes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Looking at two groups of expression profiles, one for mice fed a high carbohydrate diet and one for mice fed a low carbohydrate diet, one observes that all 40 diabetes genes are expressed at a higher level in the high carbohydrate group than the low carbohydrate group.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Regardless of whether any of these genes would have made it to a list of significantly altered genes, observing all 40 up, and none down appears unlikely to be the result of pure chance: flipping 40 heads in a row is predicted to occur about one time in a trillion attempts using a fair coin.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] For a type of cell, the group of genes whose combined expression pattern is uniquely characteristic to a given condition constitutes the gene signature of this condition.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Ideally, the gene signature can be used to select a group of patients at a specific state of a disease with accuracy that facilitates selection of treatments.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] In any case, these statistics measure how different the behavior of some small set of genes is compared to genes not in that small set.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] GSEA uses a Kolmogorov Smirnov style statistic to see whether any previously defined gene sets exhibited unusual behavior in the current expression profile.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] This leads to a multiple hypothesis testing challenge, but reasonable methods exist to address it.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Expression profiling provides new information about what genes do under various conditions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Overall, microarray technology produces reliable expression profiles.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] From this information one can generate new hypotheses about biology or test existing ones.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] However, the size and complexity of these experiments often results in a wide variety of possible interpretations.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] In many cases, analyzing expression profiling results takes far more effort than performing the initial experiments.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Most researchers use multiple statistical methods and exploratory data analysis before publishing their expression profiling results, coordinating their efforts with a bioinformatician or other expert in DNA microarrays, RNA sequencing and single cell sequencing.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-expression-profiling] Good experimental design, adequate biological replication and follow up experiments play key roles in successful expression profiling experiments.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Researchers performing high-throughput experiments that yield sets of genes (for example, genes that are differentially expressed under different conditions) often want to retrieve a functional profile of that gene set, in order to better understand the underlying biological processes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] This can be done by comparing the input gene set to each of the bins (terms) in the gene ontology – a statistical test can be performed for each bin to see if it is enriched for the input genes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] After the completion of the Human Genome Project, the problem of how to interpret and analyze it remained.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] In order to seek out genes associated with diseases, DNA microarrays were used to measure the amount of gene expression in different cells.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Microarrays on thousands of different genes were carried out, and comparisons of the results of two different cell categories, e.g. normal cells versus cancerous cells.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] However, this method of comparison is not sensitive enough to detect the subtle differences between the expression of individual genes, because diseases typically involve entire groups of genes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Multiple genes are linked to a single biological pathway, and so it is the additive change in expression within gene sets that leads to the difference in phenotypic expression.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Gene Set Enrichment Analysis was developed to focus on the changes of expression in groups of a priori defined gene sets.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] By doing so, this method resolves the problem of the undetectable, small changes in the expression of single genes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Gene set enrichment analysis uses *a priori* gene sets that have been grouped together by their involvement in the same biological pathway, or by proximal location on a chromosome.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] A database of these predefined sets can be found at the *Molecular signatures database* (MSigDB).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] In GSEA, DNA microarrays, or now RNA-Seq, are still performed and compared between two cell categories, but instead of focusing on individual genes in a long list, the focus is put on a gene set.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Researchers analyze whether the majority of genes in the set fall in the extremes of this list: the top and bottom of the list correspond to the largest differences in expression between the two cell types.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] If the gene set falls at either the top (over-expressed) or bottom (under-expressed), it is thought to be related to the phenotypic differences.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] In the method that is typically referred to as standard GSEA, there are three steps involved in the analytical process.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Estimate the statistical significance of the ES.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] This calculation is done by a phenotypic-based permutation test in order to produce a null distribution for the ES.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] The P value is determined by comparison to the null distribution.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Adjust for multiple hypothesis testing for when a large number of gene sets are being analyzed at one time.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] The enrichment scores for each set are normalized and a false discovery rate is calculated.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] When GSEA was first proposed in 2003 some immediate concerns were raised regarding its methodology.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] These criticisms led to the use of the correlation-weighted Kolmogorov–Smirnov test, the normalized ES, and the false discovery rate calculation, all of which are the factors that currently define standard GSEA.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] However, GSEA has now also been criticized for the fact that its null distribution is superfluous, and too difficult to be worth calculating, as well as the fact that its Kolmogorov–Smirnov-like statistic is not as sensitive as the original.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] As an alternative, the method known as Simpler Enrichment Analysis (SEA), was proposed.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] This method assumes gene independence and uses a simpler approach to calculate t-test.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] However, it is thought that these assumptions are in fact too simplifying, and gene correlation cannot be disregarded.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] One other limitation to Gene Set Enrichment Analysis is that the results are very dependent on the algorithm that clusters the genes, and the number of clusters being tested.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Spectral Gene Set Enrichment (SGSE) is a proposed, unsupervised test.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] The method's founders claim that it is a better way to find associations between MSigDB gene sets and microarray data.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Using the weighted Z-method to calculate the association between the gene sets and the spectral structure of the data.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] GSEA uses complicated statistics, so it requires a computer program to run the calculations.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] GSEA has become standard practice, and there are many websites and downloadable programs that will provide the data sets and run the analysis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] It outputs a downloadable graph and a list of statistically overrepresented terms in the user's list of genes using hypergeometric distribution.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] MOET also displays the corresponding Bonferroni correction and odds ratio on the results page.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] It is simple to use, and results are provided with a few clicks in seconds; no software installations or programming skills are required.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] In addition, MOET is updated weekly, providing the user with the most recent data for analyses.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] NASQAR (Nucleic Acid SeQuence Analysis Resource) is an open source, web-based platform for high-throughput sequencing data analysis and visualization.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] GSEA can be run using the R-based clusterProfiler package.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] NASQAR currently supports GO Term and KEGG Pathway enrichment with all organisms supported by an Org.Db database.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] The gene ontology (GO) annotation for 165 plant species and GO enrichment analysis is available.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] The Molecular Signatures Database hosts an extensive collection of annotated gene sets that can be used with most GSEA Software.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] The Broad Institute website is in cooperation with MSigDB and has a downloadable GSEA software, as well a general tutorial.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] WebGestalt is a web based gene set analysis toolkit.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] It supports three well-established and complementary methods for enrichment analysis, including Over-Representation Analysis (ORA), Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA), and Network Topology-based Analysis (NTA).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Analysis can be performed against 12 organisms and 321,251 functional categories using 354 gene identifiers from various databases and technology platforms.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Enrichr is a gene set enrichment analysis tool for mammalian gene sets.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] The background libraries are from over 200 resources and contain over 450,000 annotated gene sets.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] The tool can be accessed through API and provides different ways to visualize the results.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] GeneSCF is a real-time based functional enrichment tool with support for multiple organisms and is designed to overcome the problems associated with using outdated resources and databases.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] DAVID is the database for annotation, visualization and integrated discovery, a bioinformatics tool that pools together information from most major bioinformatics sources, with the aim of analyzing large gene lists in a high-throughput manner.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] DAVID goes beyond standard GSEA with additional functions like switching between gene and protein identifiers on the genome-wide scale, however, the annotations used by DAVID was not updated since October 2016 to Dec 2021, which can have a considerable impact on practical interpretation of results.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Metascape is a biologist-oriented gene-list analysis portal.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Metascape integrates pathway enrichment analysis, protein complex analysis, and multi-list meta-analysis into one seamless workflow accessible through a significantly simplified user interface.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Metascape maintains analysis accuracy by updating its 40 underlying knowledgebases monthly.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Metascape presents results using easy-to-interpret graphics, spreadsheets, and publication quality presentations, and is freely available.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] The Gene Ontology (GO) consortium has also developed their own online GO term enrichment tool, allowing species-specific enrichment analysis versus the complete database, coarser-grained GO slims, or custom references.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Genomic region enrichment of annotations tool (GREAT) is a software which takes advantage of *regulatory domains* to better associate gene ontology terms to genes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Its primary purpose is to identify pathways and processes that are significantly associated with factor regulating activity.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] This method maps genes with regulatory regions through a hypergeometric test over genes, inferring proximal gene regulatory domains.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] It does this by using the total fraction of the genome associated with a given ontology term as the expected fraction of input regions associated with the term by chance.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Enrichment is calculated by all regulatory regions, and several experiments were performed to validate GREAT, one of which being enrichment analyses done on 8 ChIP-seq datasets.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] The Functional Enrichment Analysis (FunRich) tool is mainly used for the functional enrichment and network analysis of Omics data.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] The FuncAssociate tool enables Gene Ontology and custom enrichment analyses.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] It allows inputting ordered sets as well as weighted gene space files for background.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Instances of InterMine automatically provide enrichment analysis for uploaded sets of genes and other biological entities.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] ToppGene is a one-stop portal for gene list enrichment analysis and candidate gene prioritization based on functional annotations and protein interactions network.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Developed and maintained by the Division of Biomedical Informatics at Cincinnati Children's Hospital Medical Center.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Quantitative Set Analysis for Gene Expression (QuSAGE) is a computational method for gene set enrichment analysis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] QuSAGE improves power by accounting for inter-gene correlations and quantifies gene set activity with a complete probability density function (PDF).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] From this PDF, P values and confidence intervals can be easily extracted.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Preserving the PDF also allows for post-hoc analysis (e.g., pair-wise comparisons of gene set activity) while maintaining statistical traceability.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] The applicability of QuSAGE has been extended to longitudinal studies by adding functionality for general linear mixed models.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] QuSAGE was used by the NIH/NIAID to identify baseline transcriptional signatures that were associated with human influenza vaccination responses.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] QuSAGE is available as a R/Bioconductor package.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Blast2GO is a bioinformatics platform for functional annotation and analysis of genomic datasets.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] This tool allows to perform gene set enrichment analysis, among other functions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Single-nucleotide polymorphisms, or SNPs, are single base mutations that may be associated with diseases.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] One base change has the potential to affect the protein that results from that gene being expressed; however, it also has the potential to have no effect at all.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Genome-wide association studies (GWAS) are comparisons between healthy and disease genotypes to try to find SNPs that are overrepresented in the disease genomes, and might be associated with that condition.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Before GSEA, the accuracy of genome-wide SNP association studies was severely limited by a high number of false positives.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] The theory that the SNPs contributing to a disease tend to be grouped in a set of genes that are all involved in the same biological pathway, is what the GSEA-SNP method is based on.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] This application of GSEA does not only aid in the discovery of disease-associated SNPs, but helps illuminate the corresponding pathways and mechanisms of the diseases.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Gene set enrichment methods led to the discovery of new suspect genes and biological pathways related to spontaneous preterm births.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Exome sequences from women who had experienced SPTB were compared to those from females from the 1000 Genome Project, using a tool that scored possible disease-causing variants.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Genes with higher scores were then run through different programs to group them into gene sets based on pathways and ontology groups.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] This study found that the variants were significantly clustered in sets related to several pathways, all suspects in SPTB.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Gene set enrichment analysis can be used to understand the changes that cells undergo during carcinogenesis and metastasis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] In a study, microarrays were performed on renal cell carcinoma metastases, primary renal tumors, and normal kidney tissue, and the data was analyzed using GSEA.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] This analysis showed significant changes of expression in genes involved in pathways that have not been previously associated with the progression of renal cancer.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] From this study, GSEA has provided potential new targets for renal cell carcinoma therapy.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] GSEA can be used to help understand the molecular mechanisms of complex disorders.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Schizophrenia is a largely heritable disorder, but is also very complex, and the onset of the disease involves many genes interacting within multiple pathways, as well the interaction of those genes with environmental factors.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] For instance, epigenetic changes, like DNA methylation, are affected by the environment, but are also inherently dependent on the DNA itself.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] DNA methylation is the most well-studied epigenetic change, and was recently analyzed using GSEA in relation to schizophrenia-related intermediate phenotypes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Researchers ranked genes for their correlation between methylation patterns and each of the phenotypes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] They then used GSEA to look for an enrichment of genes that are predicted to be targeted by microRNAs in the progression of the disease.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] GSEA can help provide molecular evidence for the association of biological pathways with diseases.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Previous studies have shown that long-term depression symptoms are correlated with changes in immune response and inflammatory pathways.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Genetic and molecular evidence was sought to support this.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Researchers took blood samples from sufferers of depression, and used genome-wide expression data, along with GSEA to find expression differences in gene sets related to inflammatory pathways.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] This study found that those people who rated with the most severe depression symptoms also had significant expression differences in those gene sets, and this result supports the association hypothesis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Gene set enrichment analysis has been adapted for microbiome studies through taxon set enrichment analysis (TSEA) and microbe set enrichment analysis (MSEA).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/gene-set-enrichment-analysis] Instead of analyzing gene sets, these approaches tests for enrichment of predefined sets of microbial species or genera enabling interpretation of microbial community shifts in terms of higher-level taxonomy or functional roles.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] RNA-Seq facilitates the ability to look at alternative gene spliced transcripts, post-transcriptional modifications, gene fusion, mutations/SNPs and changes in gene expression over time, or differences in gene expression in different groups or treatments.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] In addition to mRNA transcripts, RNA-Seq can look at different populations of RNA to include total RNA, small RNA, such as miRNA, tRNA, and ribosomal profiling.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] RNA-Seq can also be used to determine exon/intron boundaries and verify or amend previously annotated 5' and 3' gene boundaries.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Recent advances in RNA-Seq include single cell sequencing, bulk RNA sequencing, 3' mRNA-sequencing**,** in situ sequencing of fixed tissue, and native RNA molecule sequencing with single-molecule real-time sequencing.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Other examples of emerging RNA-Seq applications due to the advancement of bioinformatics algorithms are copy number alteration, microbial contamination, transposable elements, cell type (deconvolution) and the presence of neoantigens.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Prior to RNA-Seq, gene expression studies were done with hybridization-based microarrays.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Issues with microarrays include cross-hybridization artifacts, poor quantification of lowly and highly expressed genes, and needing to know the sequence *a priori*.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Because of these technical issues, transcriptomics transitioned to sequencing-based methods.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] These progressed from Sanger sequencing of Expressed sequence tag libraries, to chemical tag-based methods (e.g., serial analysis of gene expression), and finally to the current technology, next-gen sequencing of complementary DNA (cDNA), notably RNA-Seq in mid 2000s.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The first manuscripts that used RNA-Seq even without using the term includes those of prostate cancer cell lines (dated 2006), *Medicago truncatula* (2006), maize (2007), while the term "RNA-Seq" itself was first mentioned in 2008 .
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The number of manuscripts referring to RNA-Seq in the title or abstract (Figure, blue line) is continuously increasing with 6754 manuscripts published in 2018.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The intersection of RNA-Seq and medicine (Figure, gold line) has similar celerity.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The general steps to prepare a complementary DNA (cDNA) library for sequencing are described below, but often vary between platforms.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] RNA molecules having 3' poly(A) tails in eukaryotes are mainly composed of mature, processed, coding sequences.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Poly(A) selection is performed by mixing RNA with poly(T) oligomers covalently attached to a substrate, typically magnetic beads.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Poly(A) selection has important limitations in RNA biotype detection.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Many RNA biotypes are not polyadenylated, including many noncoding RNA and histone-core protein transcripts, or are regulated via their poly(A) tail length (e.g., cytokines) and thus might not be detected after poly(A) selection.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Furthermore, poly(A) selection may display increased 3' bias, especially with lower quality RNA.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] These limitations can be avoided with ribosomal depletion, removing rRNA that typically represents over 90% of the RNA in a cell.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Both poly(A) enrichment and ribosomal depletion steps are labor intensive and could introduce biases, so more simple approaches have been developed to omit these steps.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Small RNA targets, such as miRNA, can be further isolated through size selection with exclusion gels, magnetic beads, or commercial kits.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] *cDNA synthesis:* RNA is reverse transcribed to cDNA because DNA is more stable and to allow for amplification (which uses DNA polymerases) and leverage more mature DNA sequencing technology.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Amplification subsequent to reverse transcription results in loss of strandedness, which can be avoided with chemical labeling or single molecule sequencing.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Fragmentation and size selection are performed to purify sequences that are the appropriate length for the sequencing machine.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The RNA, cDNA, or both are fragmented with enzymes, sonication, divalent ions, or nebulizers.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Fragmentation of the RNA reduces 5' bias of randomly primed-reverse transcription and the influence of primer binding sites, with the downside that the 5' and 3' ends are converted to DNA less efficiently.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Fragmentation is followed by size selection, where either small sequences are removed or a tight range of sequence lengths are selected.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Because small RNAs like miRNAs are lost, these are analyzed independently.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The cDNA for each experiment can be indexed with a hexamer or octamer barcode, so that these experiments can be pooled into a single lane for multiplexed sequencing.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The cDNA library derived from RNA biotypes is then sequenced into a computer-readable format.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] There are many high-throughput sequencing technologies for cDNA sequencing including platforms developed by Illumina, Thermo Fisher, BGI/MGI, PacBio, and Oxford Nanopore Technologies.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Sequencing platform choice and parameters are guided by experimental design and cost.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Common experimental design considerations include deciding on the sequencing length, sequencing depth, use of single versus paired-end sequencing, number of replicates, multiplexing, randomization, and spike-ins.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] When sequencing RNA other than mRNA, the library preparation is modified.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The cellular RNA is selected based on the desired size range.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] For small RNA targets, such as miRNA, the RNA is isolated through size selection.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] This can be performed with a size exclusion gel, through size selection magnetic beads, or with a commercially developed kit.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Once isolated, linkers are added to the 3' and 5' end then purified.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The final step is cDNA generation through reverse transcription.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] This technology sequences RNA molecules directly in a massively-parallel manner.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Massively parallel single molecule direct RNA-Seq has been explored as an alternative to traditional RNA-Seq, in which RNA-to-cDNA conversion, ligation, amplification, and other sample manipulation steps may introduce biases and artefacts.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Technology platforms that perform single-molecule real-time RNA-Seq include Oxford Nanopore Technologies (ONT) Nanopore sequencing.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Sequencing RNA in its native form preserves modifications like methylation, allowing them to be investigated directly and simultaneously.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Another benefit of single-molecule direct RNA-Seq is that transcripts can be covered in full length, allowing for higher confidence isoform detection and quantification compared to short-read sequencing.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Traditionally, single-molecule RNA-Seq methods have higher error rates compared to short-read sequencing, but newer methods like ONT direct RNA-Seq have a reduced error rate.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Recent uses of ONT direct RNA-Seq for differential expression in human cell populations have demonstrated that this technology can overcome many limitations of short and long cDNA sequencing.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Standard methods such as microarrays and standard bulk RNA-Seq analysis analyze the expression of RNAs from large populations of cells.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] In mixed cell populations, these measurements may obscure critical differences between individual cells within these populations.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-Seq) provides the expression profiles of individual cells.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Although it is not possible to obtain complete information on every RNA expressed by each cell, due to the small amount of material available, patterns of gene expression can be identified through gene clustering analyses.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] This can uncover the existence of rare cell types within a cell population that may never have been seen before.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] For example, rare specialized cells in the lung called pulmonary ionocytes that express the Cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator were identified in 2018 by two groups performing scRNA-Seq on lung airway epithelia.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Expression is quantified to study cellular changes in response to external stimuli, differences between healthy and diseased states, and other research questions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Transcript levels are often used as a proxy for protein abundance, but these are often not equivalent due to post transcriptional events such as RNA interference and nonsense-mediated decay.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Expression is quantified by counting the number of reads that mapped to each locus in the transcriptome assembly step.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Expression can be quantified for exons or genes using contigs or reference transcript annotations.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] These observed RNA-Seq read counts have been robustly validated against older technologies, including expression microarrays and qPCR.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Tools that quantify counts are HTSeq, FeatureCounts, Rcount, maxcounts, FIXSEQ, and Cuffquant.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] These tools determine read counts from aligned RNA-Seq data, but alignment-free counts can also be obtained with Sailfish and Kallisto.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The read counts are then converted into appropriate metrics for hypothesis testing, regressions, and other analyses.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] RNA spike-ins are samples of RNA at known concentrations that can be used as gold standards in experimental design and during downstream analyses for absolute quantification and detection of genome-wide effects.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The simplest but often most powerful use of RNA-Seq is finding differences in gene expression between two or more conditions (*e.g.*, treated vs not treated); this process is called differential expression.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The outputs are frequently referred to as differentially expressed genes (DEGs) and these genes can either be up- or down-regulated (*i.e.*, higher or lower in the condition of interest).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] There are many tools that perform differential expression.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Most are run in R, Python, or the Unix command line.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Commonly used tools include DESeq, edgeR, and voom+limma, all of which are available through R/Bioconductor.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Downstream analyses for a list of differentially expressed genes come in two flavors, validating observations and making biological inferences.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Owing to the pitfalls of differential expression and RNA-Seq, important observations are replicated with (1) an orthogonal method in the same samples (like real-time PCR) or (2) another, sometimes pre-registered, experiment in a new cohort.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The latter helps ensure generalizability and can typically be followed up with a meta-analysis of all the pooled cohorts.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The most common method for obtaining higher-level biological understanding of the results is gene set enrichment analysis, although sometimes candidate gene approaches are employed.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Common tools for gene set enrichment include web interfaces (*e.g.*, ENRICHR, g:profiler, WEBGESTALT) and software packages.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] When evaluating enrichment results, one heuristic is to first look for enrichment of known biology as a sanity check and then expand the scope to look for novel biology.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] RNA splicing is integral to eukaryotes and contributes significantly to protein regulation and diversity, occurring in >90% of human genes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] One goal of RNA-Seq is to identify alternative splicing events and test if they differ between conditions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Long-read sequencing captures the full transcript and thus minimizes many of issues in estimating isoform abundance, like ambiguous read mapping.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Differential gene expression tools can also be used for differential isoform expression if isoforms are quantified ahead of time with other tools like RSEM.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Coexpression networks are data-derived representations of genes behaving in a similar way across tissues and experimental conditions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Their main purpose lies in hypothesis generation and guilt-by-association approaches for inferring functions of previously unknown genes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] RNA-Seq data has been used to infer genes involved in specific pathways based on Pearson correlation, both in plants and mammals.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The main advantage of RNA-Seq data in this kind of analysis over the microarray platforms is the capability to cover the entire transcriptome, therefore allowing the possibility to unravel more complete representations of the gene regulatory networks.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Differential regulation of the splice isoforms of the same gene can be detected and used to predict their biological functions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Weighted gene co-expression network analysis has been successfully used to identify co-expression modules and intramodular hub genes based on RNA seq data.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Co-expression modules may correspond to cell types or pathways.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Highly connected intramodular hubs can be interpreted as representatives of their respective module.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] An eigengene is a weighted sum of expression of all genes in a module.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Eigengenes are useful biomarkers (features) for diagnosis and prognosis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Variance-Stabilizing Transformation approaches for estimating correlation coefficients based on RNA seq data have been proposed.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] RNA-Seq captures DNA variation, including single nucleotide variants, small insertions/deletions. and structural variation.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Variant calling in RNA-Seq is similar to DNA variant calling and often employs the same tools (including SAMtools mpileup and GATK HaplotypeCaller) with adjustments to account for splicing.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] One unique dimension for RNA variants is allele-specific expression (ASE): the variants from only one haplotype might be preferentially expressed due to regulatory effects including imprinting and expression quantitative trait loci, and noncoding rare variants.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Having the matching genomic and transcriptomic sequences of an individual can help detect post-transcriptional edits (RNA editing).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] A post-transcriptional modification event is identified if the gene's transcript has an allele/variant not observed in the genomic data.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Caused by different structural modifications in the genome, fusion genes have gained attention because of their relationship with cancer.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The ability of RNA-Seq to analyze a sample's whole transcriptome in an unbiased fashion makes it an attractive tool to find these kinds of common events in cancer.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The idea follows from the process of aligning the short transcriptomic reads to a reference genome.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Most of the short reads will fall within one complete exon, and a smaller but still large set would be expected to map to known exon-exon junctions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The remaining unmapped short reads would then be further analyzed to determine whether they match an exon-exon junction where the exons come from different genes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] This would be evidence of a possible fusion event, however, because of the length of the reads, this could prove to be very noisy.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] An alternative approach is to use paired-end reads, when a potentially large number of paired reads would map each end to a different exon, giving better coverage of these events (see figure).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Nonetheless, the end result consists of multiple and potentially novel combinations of genes providing an ideal starting point for further validation.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Copy number analyses (CNA) are commonly used in cancer studies.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Gain and loss of the genes have signalling pathway implications and are a key biomarker of molecular dysfunction in oncology.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Calling the CNA information from RNA-Seq data is not straightforward because of the differences in gene expression, which lead to the read depth variance of different magnitudes across genes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Due to these difficulties, most of these analyses are usually done using whole-genome sequencing / whole-exome sequencing (WGS/WES).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] But advanced bioinformatics tools can call CNA from RNA-Seq.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] RNA-Seq has the potential to identify new disease biology, profile biomarkers for clinical indications, infer druggable pathways, and make genetic diagnoses.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] These results could be further personalized for subgroups or even individual patients, potentially highlighting more effective prevention, diagnostics, and therapy.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The feasibility of this approach is in part dictated by costs in money and time; a related limitation is the required team of specialists (bioinformaticians, physicians/clinicians, basic researchers, technicians) to fully interpret the huge amount of data generated by this analysis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] A lot of emphasis has been given to RNA-Seq data after the Encyclopedia of DNA Elements (ENCODE) and The Cancer Genome Atlas (TCGA) projects have used this approach to characterize dozens of cell lines and thousands of primary tumor samples, respectively.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] ENCODE aimed to identify genome-wide regulatory regions in different cohort of cell lines and transcriptomic data are paramount to understand the downstream effect of those epigenetic and genetic regulatory layers.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] TCGA, instead, aimed to collect and analyze thousands of patient's samples from 30 different tumor types to understand the underlying mechanisms of malignant transformation and progression.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] In this context RNA-Seq data provide a unique snapshot of the transcriptomic status of the disease and look at an unbiased population of transcripts that allows the identification of novel transcripts, fusion transcripts and non-coding RNAs that could be undetected with different technologies.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] The applications of RNA-Seq are growing day by day.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/rna-seq] Other new application of RNA-Seq includes detection of microbial contaminants, determining cell type abundance (cell type deconvolution), measuring the expression of TEs and Neoantigen prediction etc.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The first attempts to study whole transcriptomes began in the early 1990s.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Subsequent technological advances since the late 1990s have repeatedly transformed the field and made transcriptomics a widespread discipline in biological sciences.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] There are two key contemporary techniques in the field: microarrays, which quantify a set of predetermined sequences, and RNA-Seq, which uses high-throughput sequencing to record all transcripts.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] As the technology improved, the volume of data produced by each transcriptome experiment increased.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] As a result, data analysis methods have steadily been adapted to more accurately and efficiently analyse increasingly large volumes of data.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptome databases have consequently been growing bigger and more useful as transcriptomes continue to be collected and shared by researchers.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] It would be almost impossible to interpret the information contained in a transcriptome without the knowledge of previous experiments.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Measuring the expression of an organism's genes in different tissues or conditions, or at different times, gives information on how genes are regulated and reveals details of an organism's biology.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] It can also be used to infer the functions of previously unannotated genes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptome analysis has enabled greater insight into gene expression changes in different organisms and has been instrumental in the understanding of human disease.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] An analysis of gene expression in its entirety allows detection of broad coordinated trends which cannot be discerned by more targeted assays.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomics has been characterised by the development of new techniques which have redefined what is possible every decade or so and rendered previous technologies obsolete.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The first attempt at capturing a partial human transcriptome was published in 1991 and reported 609 mRNA sequences from the human brain.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] In 2008, two human transcriptomes, composed of millions of transcript-derived sequences covering 16,000 genes, were published, and by 2015 transcriptomes had been published for hundreds of individuals.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomes of different disease states, tissues, or even single cells are now routinely generated.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] This explosion in transcriptomics has been driven by the rapid development of new technologies with improved sensitivity and economy.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Studies of individual transcripts were being performed several decades before any transcriptomics approaches were available.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Libraries of silkmoth mRNA transcripts were collected and converted to complementary DNA (cDNA) for storage using reverse transcriptase in the late 1970s.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] In the 1980s, low-throughput sequencing using the Sanger method was used to sequence random transcripts, producing expressed sequence tags (ESTs).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The Sanger method of sequencing was predominant until the advent of high-throughput methods such as sequencing by synthesis (Solexa/Illumina).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] ESTs came to prominence during the 1990s as an efficient method to determine the gene content of an organism without sequencing the entire genome.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Amounts of individual transcripts were quantified using Northern blotting, nylon membrane arrays, and later reverse transcriptase quantitative PCR (RT-qPCR) methods, but these methods are laborious and can only capture a tiny subsection of a transcriptome.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Consequently, the manner in which a transcriptome as a whole is expressed and regulated remained unknown until higher-throughput techniques were developed.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The word "transcriptome" was first used in the 1990s.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] In 1995, one of the earliest sequencing-based transcriptomic methods was developed, serial analysis of gene expression (SAGE), which worked by Sanger sequencing of concatenated random transcript fragments.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcripts were quantified by matching the fragments to known genes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] A variant of SAGE using high-throughput sequencing techniques, called digital gene expression analysis, was also briefly used.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] However, these methods were largely overtaken by high throughput sequencing of entire transcripts, which provided additional information on transcript structure such as splice variants.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The dominant contemporary techniques, microarrays and RNA-Seq, were developed in the mid-1990s and 2000s.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarrays that measure the abundances of a defined set of transcripts via their hybridisation to an array of complementary probes were first published in 1995.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarray technology allowed the assay of thousands of transcripts simultaneously and at a greatly reduced cost per gene and labour saving.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Both spotted oligonucleotide arrays and Affymetrix high-density arrays were the method of choice for transcriptional profiling until the late 2000s.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Over this period, a range of microarrays were produced to cover known genes in model or economically important organisms.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Advances in design and manufacture of arrays improved the specificity of probes and allowed more genes to be tested on a single array.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Advances in fluorescence detection increased the sensitivity and measurement accuracy for low abundance transcripts.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq is accomplished by reverse transcribing RNA *in vitro* and sequencing the resulting cDNAs.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcript abundance is derived from the number of counts from each transcript.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The technique has therefore been heavily influenced by the development of high-throughput sequencing technologies.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Massively parallel signature sequencing (MPSS) was an early example based on generating 16–20 bp sequences via a complex series of hybridisations, and was used in 2004 to validate the expression of ten thousand genes in *Arabidopsis thaliana*.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The earliest RNA-Seq work was published in 2006 with one hundred thousand transcripts sequenced using 454 technology.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] This was sufficient coverage to quantify relative transcript abundance.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq began to increase in popularity after 2008 when new Solexa/Illumina technologies allowed one billion transcript sequences to be recorded.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] This yield now allows for the quantification and comparison of human transcriptomes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Generating data on RNA transcripts can be achieved via either of two main principles: sequencing of individual transcripts (ESTs, or RNA-Seq) or hybridisation of transcripts to an ordered array of nucleotide probes (microarrays).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] All transcriptomic methods require RNA to first be isolated from the experimental organism before transcripts can be recorded.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Isolated RNA may additionally be treated with DNase to digest any traces of DNA.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] It is necessary to enrich messenger RNA as total RNA extracts are typically 98% ribosomal RNA.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Enrichment for transcripts can be performed by poly-A affinity methods or by depletion of ribosomal RNA using sequence-specific probes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Degraded RNA may affect downstream results; for example, mRNA enrichment from degraded samples will result in the depletion of 5' mRNA ends and an uneven signal across the length of a transcript.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Snap-freezing of tissue prior to RNA isolation is typical, and care is taken to reduce exposure to RNase enzymes once isolation is complete.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] An expressed sequence tag (EST) is a short nucleotide sequence generated from a single RNA transcript.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA is first copied as complementary DNA (cDNA) by a reverse transcriptase enzyme before the resultant cDNA is sequenced.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Because ESTs can be collected without prior knowledge of the organism from which they come, they can be made from mixtures of organisms or environmental samples.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Although higher-throughput methods are now used, EST libraries commonly provided sequence information for early microarray designs; for example, a barley microarray was designed from 350,000 previously sequenced ESTs.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] These cDNA tags are then joined head-to-tail into long strands (>500 bp) and sequenced using low-throughput, but long read-length methods such as Sanger sequencing.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The sequences are then divided back into their original 11 bp tags using computer software in a process called deconvolution.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] If a high-quality reference genome is available, these tags may be matched to their corresponding gene in the genome.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] If a reference genome is unavailable, the tags can be directly used as diagnostic markers if found to be differentially expressed in a disease state.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The cap analysis gene expression (CAGE) method is a variant of SAGE that sequences tags from the 5' end of an mRNA transcript only.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Therefore, the transcriptional start site of genes can be identified when the tags are aligned to a reference genome.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Identifying gene start sites is of use for promoter analysis and for the cloning of full-length cDNAs.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] SAGE and CAGE methods produce information on more genes than was possible when sequencing single ESTs, but sample preparation and data analysis are typically more labour-intensive.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarrays usually consist of a grid of short nucleotide oligomers, known as "probes", typically arranged on a glass slide.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcript abundance is determined by hybridisation of fluorescently labelled transcripts to these probes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The fluorescence intensity at each probe location on the array indicates the transcript abundance for that probe sequence.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Groups of probes designed to measure the same transcript (i.e., hybridizing a specific transcript in different positions) are usually referred to as "probesets".
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarrays require some genomic knowledge from the organism of interest, for example, in the form of an annotated genome sequence, or a library of ESTs that can be used to generate the probes for the array.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarrays for transcriptomics typically fall into one of two broad categories: low-density spotted arrays or high-density short probe arrays.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcript abundance is inferred from the intensity of fluorescence derived from fluorophore-tagged transcripts that bind to the array.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Spotted low-density arrays typically feature picolitre drops of a range of purified cDNAs arrayed on the surface of a glass slide.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] These probes are longer than those of high-density arrays and cannot identify alternative splicing events.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Spotted arrays use two different fluorophores to label the test and control samples, and the ratio of fluorescence is used to calculate a relative measure of abundance.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] High-density arrays use a single fluorescent label, and each sample is hybridised and detected individually.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] High-density arrays were popularised by the Affymetrix GeneChip array, where each transcript is quantified by several short 25-mer probes that together assay one gene.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] NimbleGen arrays were a high-density array produced by a maskless-photochemistry method, which permitted flexible manufacture of arrays in small or large numbers.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] These arrays had 100,000s of 45 to 85-mer probes and were hybridised with a one-colour labelled sample for expression analysis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Some designs incorporated up to 12 independent arrays per slide.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq refers to the combination of a high-throughput sequencing methodology with computational methods to capture and quantify transcripts present in an RNA extract.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The nucleotide sequences generated are typically around 100 bp in length, but can range from 30 bp to over 10,000 bp depending on the sequencing method used.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq leverages deep sampling of the transcriptome with many short fragments from a transcriptome to allow computational reconstruction of the original RNA transcript by aligning reads to a reference genome or to each other (de novo assembly).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Both low-abundance and high-abundance RNAs can be quantified in an RNA-Seq experiment (dynamic range of 5 orders of magnitude)—a key advantage over microarray transcriptomes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] In addition, input RNA amounts are much lower for RNA-Seq (nanogram quantity) compared to microarrays (microgram quantity), which allow examination of the transcriptome even at a single-cell resolution when combined with amplification of cDNA.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Theoretically, there is no upper limit of quantification in RNA-Seq, and background noise is very low for 100 bp reads in non-repetitive regions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq may be used to identify genes within a genome, or identify which genes are active at a particular point in time, and read counts can be used to accurately model the relative gene expression level.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq methodology has constantly improved, primarily through the development of DNA sequencing technologies to increase throughput, accuracy, and read length.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Since the first descriptions in 2006 and 2008, RNA-Seq has been rapidly adopted and overtook microarrays as the dominant transcriptomics technique in 2015.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The quest for transcriptome data at the level of individual cells has driven advances in RNA-Seq library preparation methods, resulting in dramatic advances in sensitivity.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Single-cell transcriptomes are now well described and have even been extended to *in situ* RNA-Seq where transcriptomes of individual cells are directly interrogated in fixed tissues.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq was established in concert with the rapid development of a range of high-throughput DNA sequencing technologies.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] However, before the extracted RNA transcripts are sequenced, several key processing steps are performed.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Methods differ in the use of transcript enrichment, fragmentation, amplification, single or paired-end sequencing, and whether to preserve strand information.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The sensitivity of an RNA-Seq experiment can be increased by enriching classes of RNA that are of interest and depleting known abundant RNAs.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The mRNA molecules can be separated using oligonucleotides probes which bind their poly-A tails.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Alternatively, ribo-depletion can be used to specifically remove abundant but uninformative ribosomal RNAs (rRNAs) by hybridisation to probes tailored to the taxon's specific rRNA sequences (e.g. mammal rRNA, plant rRNA).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] However, ribo-depletion can also introduce some bias via non-specific depletion of off-target transcripts.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Small RNAs, such as micro RNAs, can be purified based on their size by gel electrophoresis and extraction.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Since mRNAs are longer than the read-lengths of typical high-throughput sequencing methods, transcripts are usually fragmented prior to sequencing.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The fragmentation method is a key aspect of sequencing library construction.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Fragmentation may be achieved by chemical hydrolysis, nebulisation, sonication, or reverse transcription with chain-terminating nucleotides.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Alternatively, fragmentation and cDNA tagging may be done simultaneously by using transposase enzymes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] During preparation for sequencing, cDNA copies of transcripts may be amplified by PCR to enrich for fragments that contain the expected 5' and 3' adapter sequences.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Amplification is also used to allow sequencing of very low input amounts of RNA, down to as little as 50 pg in extreme applications.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Spike-in controls of known RNAs can be used for quality control assessment to check library preparation and sequencing, in terms of GC-content, fragment length, as well as the bias due to fragment position within a transcript.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Unique molecular identifiers (UMIs) are short random sequences that are used to individually tag sequence fragments during library preparation so that every tagged fragment is unique.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] UMIs provide an absolute scale for quantification, the opportunity to correct for subsequent amplification bias introduced during library construction, and accurately estimate the initial sample size.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] UMIs are particularly well-suited to single-cell RNA-Seq transcriptomics, where the amount of input RNA is restricted and extended amplification of the sample is required.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Once the transcript molecules have been prepared they can be sequenced in just one direction (single-end) or both directions (paired-end).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] A single-end sequence is usually quicker to produce, cheaper than paired-end sequencing and sufficient for quantification of gene expression levels.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Paired-end sequencing produces more robust alignments/assemblies, which is beneficial for gene annotation and transcript isoform discovery.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Strand-specific RNA-Seq methods preserve the strand information of a sequenced transcript.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Without strand information, reads can be aligned to a gene locus but do not inform in which direction the gene is transcribed.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Stranded-RNA-Seq is useful for deciphering transcription for genes that overlap in different directions and to make more robust gene predictions in non-model organisms.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Legend: NCBI SRA – National center for biotechnology information sequence read archive.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Currently RNA-Seq relies on copying RNA molecules into cDNA molecules prior to sequencing; therefore, the subsequent platforms are the same for transcriptomic and genomic data.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Consequently, the development of DNA sequencing technologies has been a defining feature of RNA-Seq.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Direct sequencing of RNA using nanopore sequencing represents a current state-of-the-art RNA-Seq technique.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Nanopore sequencing of RNA can detect modified bases that would be otherwise masked when sequencing cDNA and also eliminates amplification steps that can otherwise introduce bias.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The sensitivity and accuracy of an RNA-Seq experiment are dependent on the number of reads obtained from each sample.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] A large number of reads are needed to ensure sufficient coverage of the transcriptome, enabling detection of low abundance transcripts.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Experimental design is further complicated by sequencing technologies with a limited output range, the variable efficiency of sequence creation, and variable sequence quality.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Added to those considerations is that every species has a different number of genes and therefore requires a tailored sequence yield for an effective transcriptome.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Early studies determined suitable thresholds empirically, but as the technology matured suitable coverage was predicted computationally by transcriptome saturation.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Somewhat counter-intuitively, the most effective way to improve detection of differential expression in low expression genes is to add more biological replicates rather than adding more reads.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The current benchmarks recommended by the Encyclopedia of DNA Elements (ENCODE) Project are for 70-fold exome coverage for standard RNA-Seq and up to 500-fold exome coverage to detect rare transcripts and isoforms.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomics methods are highly parallel and require significant computation to produce meaningful data for both microarray and RNA-Seq experiments.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarray data is recorded as high-resolution images, requiring feature detection and spectral analysis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarray raw image files are each about 750 MB in size, while the processed intensities are around 60 MB in size.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Multiple short probes matching a single transcript can reveal details about the intron-exon structure, requiring statistical models to determine the authenticity of the resulting signal.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq studies produce billions of short DNA sequences, which must be aligned to reference genomes composed of millions to billions of base pairs.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] *De novo* assembly of reads within a dataset requires the construction of highly complex sequence graphs.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq operations are highly repetitious and benefit from parallelised computation but modern algorithms mean consumer computing hardware is sufficient for simple transcriptomics experiments that do not require *de novo* assembly of reads.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] A human transcriptome could be accurately captured using RNA-Seq with 30 million 100 bp sequences per sample.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] This example would require approximately 1.8 gigabytes of disk space per sample when stored in a compressed fastq format.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Processed count data for each gene would be much smaller, equivalent to processed microarray intensities.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Sequence data may be stored in public repositories, such as the Sequence Read Archive (SRA).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq datasets can be uploaded via the Gene Expression Omnibus.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarray image processing must correctly identify the regular grid of features within an image and independently quantify the fluorescence intensity for each feature.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Image artefacts must be additionally identified and removed from the overall analysis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Fluorescence intensities directly indicate the abundance of each sequence, since the sequence of each probe on the array is already known.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The first steps of RNA-seq also include similar image processing; however, conversion of images to sequence data is typically handled automatically by the instrument software.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The Illumina sequencing-by-synthesis method results in an array of clusters distributed over the surface of a flow cell.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The flow cell is imaged up to four times during each sequencing cycle, with tens to hundreds of cycles in total.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Flow cell clusters are analogous to microarray spots and must be correctly identified during the early stages of the sequencing process.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] In Roche's pyrosequencing method, the intensity of emitted light determines the number of consecutive nucleotides in a homopolymer repeat.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] There are many variants on these methods, each with a different error profile for the resulting data.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq experiments generate a large volume of raw sequence reads which have to be processed to yield useful information.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Data analysis usually requires a combination of bioinformatics software tools (see also List of RNA-Seq bioinformatics tools) that vary according to the experimental design and goals.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The process can be broken down into four stages: quality control, alignment, quantification, and differential expression.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Most popular RNA-Seq programs are run from a command-line interface, either in a Unix environment or within the R/Bioconductor statistical environment.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Sequence reads are not perfect, so the accuracy of each base in the sequence needs to be estimated for downstream analyses.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Raw data is examined to ensure: quality scores for base calls are high, the GC content matches the expected distribution, short sequence motifs (k-mers) are not over-represented, and the read duplication rate is acceptably low.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Several software options exist for sequence quality analysis, including FastQC and FaQCs.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Abnormalities may be removed (trimming) or tagged for special treatment during later processes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] In order to link sequence read abundance to the expression of a particular gene, transcript sequences are aligned to a reference genome or *de novo* aligned to one another if no reference is available.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The key challenges for alignment software include sufficient speed to permit billions of short sequences to be aligned in a meaningful timeframe, flexibility to recognise and deal with intron splicing of eukaryotic mRNA, and correct assignment of reads that map to multiple locations.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Software advances have greatly addressed these issues, and increases in sequencing read length reduce the chance of ambiguous read alignments.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] A list of currently available high-throughput sequence aligners is maintained by the EBI.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Alignment of primary transcript mRNA sequences derived from eukaryotes to a reference genome requires specialised handling of intron sequences, which are absent from mature mRNA.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Short read aligners perform an additional round of alignments specifically designed to identify splice junctions, informed by canonical splice site sequences and known intron splice site information.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Identification of intron splice junctions prevents reads from being misaligned across splice junctions or erroneously discarded, allowing more reads to be aligned to the reference genome and improving the accuracy of gene expression estimates.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Since gene regulation may occur at the mRNA isoform level, splice-aware alignments also permit detection of isoform abundance changes that would otherwise be lost in a bulked analysis.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Legend: RAM – random access memory; MPI – message passing interface; EST – expressed sequence tag.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Quantification of sequence alignments may be performed at the gene, exon, or transcript level.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Typical outputs include a table of read counts for each feature supplied to the software; for example, for genes in a general feature format file.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Gene and exon read counts may be calculated quite easily using HTSeq, for example.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Quantitation at the transcript level is more complicated and requires probabilistic methods to estimate transcript isoform abundance from short read information; for example, using cufflinks software.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Reads that align equally well to multiple locations must be identified and either removed, aligned to one of the possible locations, or aligned to the most probable location.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Some quantification methods can circumvent the need for an exact alignment of a read to a reference sequence altogether.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The kallisto software method combines pseudoalignment and quantification into a single step that runs 2 orders of magnitude faster than contemporary methods such as those used by tophat/cufflinks software, with less computational burden.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Once quantitative counts of each transcript are available, differential gene expression is measured by normalising, modelling, and statistically analysing the data.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Most tools will read a table of genes and read counts as their input, but some programs, such as cuffdiff, will accept binary alignment map format read alignments as input.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The final outputs of these analyses are gene lists with associated pair-wise tests for differential expression between treatments and the probability estimates of those differences.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomic analyses may be validated using an independent technique, for example, quantitative PCR (qPCR), which is recognisable and statistically assessable.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Gene expression is measured against defined standards both for the gene of interest and control genes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The measurement by qPCR is similar to that obtained by RNA-Seq wherein a value can be calculated for the concentration of a target region in a given sample. qPCR is, however, restricted to amplicons smaller than 300 bp, usually toward the 3' end of the coding region, avoiding the 3'UTR.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] If validation of transcript isoforms is required, an inspection of RNA-Seq read alignments should indicate where qPCR primers might be placed for maximum discrimination.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The measurement of multiple control genes along with the genes of interest produces a stable reference within a biological context. qPCR validation of RNA-Seq data has generally shown that different RNA-Seq methods are highly correlated.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Functional validation of key genes is an important consideration for post transcriptome planning.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Observed gene expression patterns may be functionally linked to a phenotype by an independent knock-down/rescue study in the organism of interest.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomic strategies have seen broad application across diverse areas of biomedical research, including disease diagnosis and profiling.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq approaches have allowed for the large-scale identification of transcriptional start sites, uncovered alternative promoter usage, and novel splicing alterations.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] These regulatory elements are important in human disease and, therefore, defining such variants is crucial to the interpretation of disease-association studies.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq can also identify disease-associated single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs), allele-specific expression, and gene fusions, which contributes to the understanding of disease causal variants.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Retrotransposons are transposable elements which proliferate within eukaryotic genomes through a process involving reverse transcription.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq can provide information about the transcription of endogenous retrotransposons that may influence the transcription of neighboring genes by various epigenetic mechanisms that lead to disease.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Similarly, the potential for using RNA-Seq to understand immune-related disease is expanding rapidly due to the ability to dissect immune cell populations and to sequence T cell and B cell receptor repertoires from patients.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq of human pathogens has become an established method for quantifying gene expression changes, identifying novel virulence factors, predicting antibiotic resistance, and unveiling host-pathogen immune interactions.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] A primary aim of this technology is to develop optimised infection control measures and targeted individualised treatment.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomic analysis has predominantly focused on either the host or the pathogen.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Dual RNA-Seq has been applied to simultaneously profile RNA expression in both the pathogen and host throughout the infection process.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] This technique enables the study of the dynamic response and interspecies gene regulatory networks in both interaction partners from initial contact through to invasion and the final persistence of the pathogen or clearance by the host immune system.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomics allows identification of genes and pathways that respond to and counteract biotic and abiotic environmental stresses.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The non-targeted nature of transcriptomics allows the identification of novel transcriptional networks in complex systems.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] For example, comparative analysis of a range of chickpea lines at different developmental stages identified distinct transcriptional profiles associated with drought and salinity stresses, including identifying the role of transcript isoforms of AP2-EREBP.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Investigation of gene expression during biofilm formation by the fungal pathogen *Candida albicans* revealed a co-regulated set of genes critical for biofilm establishment and maintenance.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomic profiling also provides crucial information on mechanisms of drug resistance.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] The use of transcriptomics is also important to investigate responses in the marine environment.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] In marine ecology, "stress" and "adaptation" have been among the most common research topics, especially related to anthropogenic stress, such as global change and pollution.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Most of the studies in this area have been done in animals, although invertebrates have been underrepresented.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] One issue still is a deficiency in functional genetic studies, which hamper gene annotations, especially for non-model species, and can lead to vague conclusions on the effects of responses studied.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomics is particularly useful for studying how bacterial genes respond to complex plant-associated environments, where adaptation is driven by coordinated regulation of multiple genes rather than single, well-characterized factors.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] In plant–microbe interactions, transcriptomic analyses have identified sets of bacterial genes that are specifically induced during plant colonization or in response to plant-derived signals, many of which lack prior functional annotation and would not be detected using targeted approaches.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] By integrating gene expression data with comparative genomic or community-level analyses, transcriptomics helps link bacterial gene regulation to ecological relevance and adaptive processes in plant-associated niches.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] This approach has proven valuable for identifying previously overlooked bacterial functions involved in stress tolerance, host interaction, and niche adaptation.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] All transcriptomic techniques have been particularly useful in identifying the functions of genes and identifying those responsible for particular phenotypes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomics of *Arabidopsis* ecotypes that hyperaccumulate metals correlated genes involved in metal uptake, tolerance, and homeostasis with the phenotype.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Integration of RNA-Seq datasets across different tissues has been used to improve annotation of gene functions in commercially important organisms (e.g. cucumber) or threatened species (e.g. koala).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Assembly of RNA-Seq reads is not dependent on a reference genome and so is ideal for gene expression studies of non-model organisms with non-existing or poorly developed genomic resources.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] For example, a database of SNPs used in Douglas fir breeding programs was created by *de novo* transcriptome analysis in the absence of a sequenced genome.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Similarly, genes that function in the development of cardiac, muscle, and nervous tissue in lobsters were identified by comparing the transcriptomes of the various tissue types without use of a genome sequence.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq can also be used to identify previously unknown protein coding regions in existing sequenced genomes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomics is most commonly applied to the mRNA content of the cell.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] However, the same techniques are equally applicable to non-coding RNAs (ncRNAs) that are not translated into a protein, but instead have direct functions (e.g. roles in protein translation, DNA replication, RNA splicing, and transcriptional regulation).
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Many of these ncRNAs affect disease states, including cancer, cardiovascular, and neurological diseases.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomics studies generate large amounts of data that have potential applications far beyond the original aims of an experiment.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] As such, raw or processed data may be deposited in public databases to ensure their utility for the broader scientific community.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/transcriptomics-technologies] For example, as of 2018, the Gene Expression Omnibus contained millions of experiments.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] In statistics, a **volcano plot** is a type of scatter-plot that is used to quickly identify changes in large data sets composed of replicate data.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] It plots significance versus fold-change on the y and x axes, respectively.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] These plots are increasingly common in omic experiments such as genomics, proteomics, and metabolomics where one often has a list of many thousands of replicate data points between two conditions and one wishes to quickly identify the most meaningful changes.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] A volcano plot is a sophisticated data visualization tool used in statistical and genomic analyses to illustrate the relationship between the magnitude of change and statistical significance.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] It is constructed by plotting the negative logarithm (base 10) of the p-value on the y-axis, ensuring that data points with lower p-values—indicative of higher statistical significance—are positioned toward the top of the plot.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] The x-axis represents the logarithm of the fold change between two conditions, allowing for a symmetric representation of both upregulated and downregulated changes relative to the center.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] This transformation ensures that equivalent deviations in either direction are equidistant from the origin, facilitating intuitive interpretation.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] The plot inherently highlights two critical regions of interest: data points that reside in the upper extremes of the graph while being significantly displaced to the left or right.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] These points correspond to variables that exhibit both substantial fold changes (magnitude of effect) and exceptional statistical significance, making them prime candidates for further investigation in differential analyses.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] The volcano plot, therefore, serves as a powerful means of identifying key biomarkers, differentially expressed genes, or other significant entities within complex datasets.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] Additional information can be added by coloring the points according to a third dimension of data (such as signal intensity), but this is not uniformly employed.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] Volcano plots are also used to graphically display a significance analysis of microarrays (SAM) gene selection criterion, an example of regularization.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] The concept of volcano plot can be generalized to other applications, where the x axis is related to a measure of the strength of a statistical signal, and y axis is related to a measure of the statistical significance of the signal.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] For example, in a genetic association case-control study, such as genome-wide association study, a point in a volcano plot represents a single-nucleotide polymorphism.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] Its x value can be the logarithm of the odds ratio and its y value can be -log10 of the p value from a Chi-square test or a Chi-square test statistic.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] Volcano plots show a characteristic upwards two arm shape because the x axis, i.e. the underlying log2-fold changes, are generally normal distributed whereas the y axis, the log10-p values, tend toward greater significance for fold-changes that deviate more strongly from zero.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] which is a parabola whose arms reach upwards on the right and left sides.
[src:gene-expression-analysis/volcano-plot-statistics] The upper bound of the data is one parabola and the lower bound is another parabola.
